      <h1>How Progressive Tax Brackets Work in the US</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>Jun 25, 2026</span><span>·</span><span>6 min read</span></div>
      <p class="article-intro">A common tax myth is that moving into a higher tax bracket reduces your take-home pay. Here is a clear, simple guide explaining how progressive tax brackets actually work.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container" style="max-width:740px;">
    <div class="prose">
      <div class="callout"><strong>Quick definition:</strong> In a progressive tax system, your income is taxed in chunks or "brackets" at increasing rates. Getting a raise only taxes the extra money at the higher rate, never your entire income.</div>

      <h2>What is a progressive tax system?</h2>
      <p>The US federal income tax system is progressive, which means that individuals with higher taxable incomes pay higher tax rates. However, these rates are not applied to your total earnings in a single lump sum. Instead, your income is divided into segments, and each segment is taxed at its corresponding rate. As your income increases, only the portion that crosses into the next bracket is taxed at the higher rate.</p>

      <h2>Marginal tax rate vs. Effective tax rate</h2>
      <p>Understanding the difference between these two rates is crucial for financial planning:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Marginal Tax Rate:</strong> This is the tax bracket your highest dollar falls into. It is the percentage of tax you pay on the next dollar you earn.</li>
        <li><strong>Effective Tax Rate:</strong> This is your actual tax rate. It is calculated by dividing your total tax liability by your total taxable income. Your effective tax rate is always lower than your marginal tax rate.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>A hypothetical tax bracket example</h2>
      <p>Let's look at how tax brackets are applied using a simplified model. Imagine the tax rates are:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>10% on income up to $11,000</li>
        <li>12% on income between $11,001 and $44,725</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If you earn $20,000 in taxable income, your tax is calculated in two steps:</p>
      <pre><code>First bracket:  $11,000 taxed at 10% = $1,100
Second bracket: ($20,000 - $11,000) = $9,000 taxed at 12% = $1,080
Total tax:      $1,100 + $1,080 = $2,180</code></pre>
      <p>Even though your highest tax bracket (marginal rate) is 12%, your actual tax rate (effective rate) is only 10.9% ($2,180 ÷ $20,000).</p>

      <h2>Why moving up a bracket never hurts your earnings</h2>
      <p>Because tax brackets only apply to income within that specific range, earning more money will always increase your take-home pay. If a raise pushes you from the 12% bracket into the 22% bracket, only the dollars earned above the threshold are taxed at 22%. The money you earned below that threshold continues to be taxed at the lower 10% and 12% rates.</p>

      <h2>How to lower your tax bracket</h2>
      <p>You can reduce your taxable income and potentially slide into a lower tax bracket by utilizing deductions and pretax contributions:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Contribute to a traditional 401(k) or IRA.</li>
        <li>Fund a Health Savings Account (HSA) or Flexible Spending Account (FSA).</li>
        <li>Claim deductions such as student loan interest or charitable donations.</li>
      </ul>
